00:00:02.340 --> 00:00:05.880
&gt;&gt;Presenter: Hello everyone and welcome to
yet another Google live installment of Authors

00:00:05.880 --> 00:00:12.650
at Google in San Francisco. We've got today
a science writer, Marc Kaufman, speaking on

00:00:12.650 --> 00:00:19.440
his book 'First Contact'. And although I can't
yet say we've definitively found life on other

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:23.750
planets, I think we've got a lot of great
updates from the science community as to how

00:00:23.750 --> 00:00:28.980
far we've progressed and how close we're coming
to at least understanding what it means when

00:00:28.980 --> 00:00:34.000
we say 'extraterrestrial life' and what we
could possibly learn from it. This is Marc's

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.910
first book. Although we're very excited to
showcase it, it will also be featured as part

00:00:38.910 --> 00:00:44.370
of the National Book Festival in the National
Mall in DC. He's been interviewed on Fresh

00:00:44.370 --> 00:00:50.250
Air on NPR and we are happy to welcome him
as part of the Authors at Google series. Thanks.

00:00:50.250 --> 00:00:54.219
[applause]
&gt;&gt;Marc Kaufman: Thanks very much. Thank you

00:00:54.219 --> 00:00:59.410
all very much. I am really delighted to be
here. I feel in a sense that we are kind of

00:00:59.410 --> 00:01:08.079
kindred spirits in a sense that I was really
drawn into a subject that is extremely cutting

00:01:08.079 --> 00:01:14.069
edge and that could not have existed 15 years
ago in terms of the kinds of information that's

00:01:14.069 --> 00:01:19.209
really being generated now, just as you are.
We have knowledge and we have technology that

00:01:19.209 --> 00:01:24.659
didn't exist before and we're now able to
find things that we couldn't before. So this

00:01:24.659 --> 00:01:31.539
is a remarkable time particularly in this
world of, of life beyond earth. And just a

00:01:31.539 --> 00:01:35.299
little bit about myself. I'm a reporter at
the Washington Post. I've been there for 10

00:01:35.299 --> 00:01:39.760
years or so. I used to be at the Philadelphia
Inquirer. I've been a foreign correspondent

00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:44.590
a lot and I'll get into it later. I kind of
came linked into being a science writer but

00:01:44.590 --> 00:01:48.810
it is extraordinarily cool and I am very glad
I was able to do it. All right, so here we

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:53.640
go. This is, I put together some slides here
and we'll just kind of talk about them as

00:01:53.640 --> 00:02:02.169
we go along. And feel free to ask questions
along the time, along the discussion.

00:02:02.169 --> 00:02:08.149
As when you think about it, there has really
been since the beginning of humankind as far

00:02:08.149 --> 00:02:16.769
as we know a desire, an instinct, to see life
or to feel that there is life in the skies.

00:02:16.769 --> 00:02:21.920
You think about where's heaven? It's up in
the skies. Where's God? Up in the skies. Where,

00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:30.489
where are angels? Or in more recent, more
secular days, E.T. and Star Wars and whatever

00:02:30.489 --> 00:02:36.850
else. There's just kind of an innate desire
to, for that to be true. And that's, you kind

00:02:36.850 --> 00:02:42.680
of wonder is that a, just a simple hope that
we're not alone in the world or in the universe

00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:47.579
or is it something kind of instinctive, kind
of deep inside of us that we can't really

00:02:47.579 --> 00:02:56.849
parse through. As, as this issue has been
dealt with over the years and it has been

00:02:56.849 --> 00:03:03.290
very kind of vociferously argued going back
to the Greeks and Romans as to whether or

00:03:03.290 --> 00:03:09.900
not there, there can be planets outside of
the Solar System and so on. And then life

00:03:09.900 --> 00:03:16.030
outside it, it has all been on the basis of
belief because they didn't really have any

00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:22.010
scientific knowledge to work with or they
would, there was a rational kind of aspect

00:03:22.010 --> 00:03:28.739
to it where they would try to impute certain
knowledge but it really was ultimately based

00:03:28.739 --> 00:03:33.349
on belief and in that sense, it ran into a
lot of obstacles.

00:03:33.349 --> 00:03:39.079
This is a statue of Giordano Bruno who is
kind of the patron saint of astrobiology which

00:03:39.079 --> 00:03:45.099
is the science that we're going to be talking
about today. He was a Dominican monk who later

00:03:45.099 --> 00:03:52.010
became a free thinker of sorts and was a believer
in what was called the multiplicity of worlds

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:55.049
which meant he thought that there were a lot
of different planets out there and that there

00:03:55.049 --> 00:03:58.890
were different people who lived on them or
different beings. And he was burned at the

00:03:58.890 --> 00:04:07.219
stake. That was, he also had, had been involved
in what was considered a number of other heresies

00:04:07.219 --> 00:04:13.080
but that was, I think, number two or three.
So it was , this is a subject that, that brings

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:20.139
up surprisingly strong emotions as again we
will get into in the future, as we go further.

00:04:20.139 --> 00:04:23.810
But this is, as I saying before, kind of new
to human kind that there is, there really

00:04:23.810 --> 00:04:35.850
is a science to ET life. It is called 'astrobiology'.
And it is a remarkable kind of umbrella discipline

00:04:35.850 --> 00:04:44.550
in the sense that it includes everything from
microbiology, geo-microbiology, chemistry,

00:04:44.550 --> 00:04:54.340
planetary science, geology, all the way to
cosmology. And it, none of those are themselves

00:04:54.340 --> 00:05:03.120
necessarily astrobiology. But there has been
a real instinct in, in and an organized effort

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:09.450
in the last 10 years, or 15 years or so to
bring it together into a particular overriding

00:05:09.450 --> 00:05:15.840
discipline. Every two years they have a, a
conference. There was one in Santa Clara two

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:22.490
years ago, one in Texas this year. About 10,000
people show up, some of the best and brightest

00:05:22.490 --> 00:05:29.080
scientists on earth. And they, they talk about
astrobiology from the perspective of their

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:36.020
own fields for the most part. But it's all
with that, that movement forward toward, 'Hey,

00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:39.950
we think that there's life out there and we're
gonna try to one, understand what that life

00:05:39.950 --> 00:05:45.639
might be; two, how we might identify it; three,
how we could maybe figure out that it was

00:05:45.639 --> 00:05:49.669
there once before and isn't there anymore'
and so on.

00:05:49.669 --> 00:05:59.099
So there I've kind of taken to, to likening
it to a stealth Apollo program. It is a massive

00:05:59.099 --> 00:06:03.300
effort. It's going on around the world. There
are tens, hundreds of thousands of scientists

00:06:03.300 --> 00:06:09.680
involved in one way or another in, in the
pursuit but until recently very few people

00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:14.530
have really known about it. And I think even
now, you know about specific bits of news

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:19.360
that come up but you don't necessarily, there
isn't a general understanding that this has

00:06:19.360 --> 00:06:25.720
been hardwired into a NASA and the European
Space Administration and to the whole effort

00:06:25.720 --> 00:06:34.410
of dealing with life beyond, with space issues
generally. Astrobiology is right at the center

00:06:34.410 --> 00:06:39.820
of it.
As I was saying, I was a foreign correspondent,

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:45.510
a lot of other things until I became a science
writer five, six years ago. My editor said,

00:06:45.510 --> 00:06:49.310
'You know, you should really learn a little
bit more about this.' So I went up to a journalism

00:06:49.310 --> 00:06:56.060
boot camp at MIT and the subject was the universe.
We were supposed to learn about all, everything

00:06:56.060 --> 00:07:01.440
in the universe in four days. I'm not sure
we succeeded but we did learn a lot about

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:06.810
super massive black holes, the Big Bang and
how galaxies are formed. And all of it was

00:07:06.810 --> 00:07:13.090
deeply fascinating. But it wasn't until this
woman arrived that, that things really gelled

00:07:13.090 --> 00:07:23.729
for me. She is, her name is Sara Seager. She
is a, she has a named chair at MIT and tenure

00:07:23.729 --> 00:07:31.530
which she got at age 34. So you can imagine
that she is like a total whiz. And she got

00:07:31.530 --> 00:07:38.690
up there and she said, 'In my lifetime, I
am almost virtually sure that we will find

00:07:38.690 --> 00:07:45.159
life beyond Earth.' And there I was, at MIT,
and this was someone who obviously knew a

00:07:45.159 --> 00:07:50.900
great deal about this and was speaking with
a lot of authority. So I said to myself, not

00:07:50.900 --> 00:07:56.440
so much as a science, as a science, from the
perspective of science, since my perspective

00:07:56.440 --> 00:08:01.210
in science then was somewhat limited. But
as a journalist, which I had been for a long

00:08:01.210 --> 00:08:07.759
time, I said, 'What a story.' You know, no
one is really looking at this in the sense

00:08:07.759 --> 00:08:16.330
of telling the, the public as it were that,
that is what the best and the brightest are

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:27.530
beginning to or have concluded, that we're
on that kind of trajectory and it's just a

00:08:27.530 --> 00:08:32.861
question of time. Just want to start a little
bit in terms of stepping back. A lot of astrobiology

00:08:32.861 --> 00:08:39.670
now involves the search for and the understanding
of microbial life and there's an instinct,

00:08:39.670 --> 00:08:43.130
perhaps not here but in some places to say,
'Well they're just little microbes. You can't

00:08:43.130 --> 00:08:53.070
see them. What's the big deal?' But as you
can see, for three billion of the 3.8 billion

00:08:53.070 --> 00:08:57.170
years that there have been, that there has
been life on Earth, it was just microbes.

00:08:57.170 --> 00:09:02.480
So all of us and everything else that you
see around here that's living, came out of

00:09:02.480 --> 00:09:09.270
that soup of single cell organisms that was,
what was life here for most of the time that

00:09:09.270 --> 00:09:16.010
there has been life. So microbes are a big
deal. And this gets into the world of extremophiles

00:09:16.010 --> 00:09:23.770
which are microbes that live in places where
they should not be living. The research on

00:09:23.770 --> 00:09:30.310
this started a number of decades ago but really
has picked up in the last 10 and then 5 years.

00:09:30.310 --> 00:09:35.900
It began with the black smokers. These are
hydrothermal vents at the bottom of oceans,

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:44.370
basically something akin to a volcano erupting
there. The temperatures get up to 750 degrees.

00:09:44.370 --> 00:09:52.670
There is nothing living right there at the
750 degrees but if you go out to 250, 200

00:09:52.670 --> 00:09:57.380
which everyone assumed was well too high for
anything to survive, they're finding thriving

00:09:57.380 --> 00:10:00.420
microbial communities. And if you go a little
bit further, you're going to find these long

00:10:00.420 --> 00:10:10.310
tubeworms which is extremely bizarre.
In ice, this is a relatively new set of understandings.

00:10:10.310 --> 00:10:18.590
This was being done at the Taylor Glacier
near, outside McMurdo in Antarctica. Researchers

00:10:18.590 --> 00:10:25.120
go there. They dig into glaciers and they
find, they take out cubes, bring them home,

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:33.130
melt them and they find microbial life. It
turns out that, that when the ice crystallizes,

00:10:33.130 --> 00:10:38.180
the H-2-O really stays in the center. Everything
else, salts, everything that isn't H-2-O is

00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:44.500
kind of kicked out to a little tiny river
or whatever outside and that is the environment

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:49.230
in which the microbes survive. They get the
nutrients because it's been kicked out and

00:10:49.230 --> 00:10:57.320
they are able and they have some kind of fluid
that they can, that they can work in. Until

00:10:57.320 --> 00:11:05.700
1995, there was no knowledge really that,
that underneath the ice of Antarctica, there

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:12.580
is a huge set of lakes including Lake Vostok
which is roughly the size of Lake Ontario.

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:20.000
It's two miles down and the Russians are right
at the very edge of breaking through and into

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:25.770
Lake Vostok. They've been finding microbial
life along with other researchers all the

00:11:25.770 --> 00:11:30.640
way down and the expectation is that down
in this lake, two miles down, they're gonna

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:34.940
find all kinds of living things.

00:11:34.940 --> 00:11:41.460
Mono Lake in your neighborhood and its arsenic
bugs. You perhaps have read about this in

00:11:41.460 --> 00:11:45.680
recent months and actually just today, there's
been additional information about it. This

00:11:45.680 --> 00:11:53.960
was, there are two things going on here. Mono
Lake is a terminal lake. It doesn't go anywhere

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:58.860
so elements get very highly concentrated.
Arsenic runs off the Sierra Nevadas and into

00:11:58.860 --> 00:12:05.200
here and so there's more arsenic here than
I think anywhere else. So it was interesting

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:10.240
when they found microbial life living in the
arsenic. But then some researchers took it

00:12:10.240 --> 00:12:18.630
a step further and basically just doing benchwork
to begin with, worked on these microbes to

00:12:18.630 --> 00:12:27.490
the point where they were, they were, essentially
the arsenic had replaced phosphorus which

00:12:27.490 --> 00:12:32.371
everyone believes, and had believed until
that point, was essential for all DNA, for

00:12:32.371 --> 00:12:41.330
all cell membranes, for a lot of other things
in the cell. And she had a paper, Felisa Wolfe-Simon

00:12:41.330 --> 00:12:51.320
had a paper published last fall in which she
said,' We believe that, that these are creatures

00:12:51.320 --> 00:12:58.220
that are entirely differ, potentially entirely
different than anything else that has originated

00:12:58.220 --> 00:13:03.350
on Earth because it in fact does not have
the phosphorus but rather has the arsenic.'

00:13:03.350 --> 00:13:08.510
It's a, it's a, the whole world is called
the 'Shadow Biosphere' and it raises the question

00:13:08.510 --> 00:13:14.560
of, 'Well, if there was a genesis of life
here on Earth once, why not twice? Why not

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:21.210
three times? And what might be out there that
we're just not looking for and is there but

00:13:21.210 --> 00:13:27.190
is, is in different forms that we, we would
not be identifying.' Very controversial. She

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:32.620
got clobbered for some of her research. And
the Blogosphere just went wild on this for

00:13:32.620 --> 00:13:40.850
some time. Just yesterday, her rebuttal was
published in the Journal of Science and basically

00:13:40.850 --> 00:13:47.170
she said, 'We think that we're on to something
here.' And while she's gotten a lot of enemies,

00:13:47.170 --> 00:13:54.360
she got a lot of collaborators as well.
The Atacama Desert in Northern Chile, the

00:13:54.360 --> 00:14:02.090
driest place on Earth. NASA goes down there
a lot for, for Mars Missions to see what conditions

00:14:02.090 --> 00:14:07.250
would be like. It rains in some of the places
once every 10 years. You know a little bit

00:14:07.250 --> 00:14:11.980
of rain and yet underneath the rocks, you
go down a little bit, you're gonna find again

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:19.080
microbial life; something that wasn't known
until 5, 10 years ago. I thought you folks

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:27.050
in particular would enjoy this. This is a,
an autonomous submersible that has been tested

00:14:27.050 --> 00:14:35.500
down in Antarctica under the glacial ice in
one of these lakes and it can go on its own

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:42.830
up to a mile and a half, two miles and, and
collects data and it can make some kinds of

00:14:42.830 --> 00:14:48.300
autonomous decisions about what might be interesting
and what might not be and then can come back

00:14:48.300 --> 00:14:55.820
to this hole and come back up. This is not
so much an issue of being able to find things

00:14:55.820 --> 00:15:02.470
we didn't know was there but it's, the technology
is gradually being put together for future

00:15:02.470 --> 00:15:08.190
missions, and this is all about Europa. The
moon of Jupiter which is, has a huge crust

00:15:08.190 --> 00:15:16.560
of ice and a vast ocean underneath the ice
and the expectation now is that it's, it's

00:15:16.560 --> 00:15:20.770
one of the best possible locations for finding
[inaudible]. And of course, it's not going

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:24.860
to be easy getting through 14 miles of ice
to get through it. You might have to bring

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:31.290
in a nuclear weapon or something. But we'll
see how that works out. In any case, Tullis

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:38.661
Onstott, he's now at Princeton and a well-known
professor but he started off in the world

00:15:38.661 --> 00:15:44.170
of extremophiles as an unknown guy. He had
no funding from NSF, no funding from anyone,

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:52.860
from NASA, anyone. He had done some original
work on, on looking for microbial life deep

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:59.870
underground, not in water but under the soil.
And was not really getting too far so he said,

00:15:59.870 --> 00:16:06.890
'Okay. Where can I go really deeply down?'
And did research and found the deepest mines

00:16:06.890 --> 00:16:13.630
on earth are in South Africa, the gold mines,
diamond mines. He took $6000 of his own money

00:16:13.630 --> 00:16:18.510
and went to South Africa and made connections
with some scientists there and over a period

00:16:18.510 --> 00:16:25.760
of a couple of years was able to go into some
of the mines and to go, you can't really see

00:16:25.760 --> 00:16:30.160
it too well here but this is a bore hole where
a little bit of water is coming out. They

00:16:30.160 --> 00:16:37.790
would collect the water and then take it into
their labs and see what they found. And after

00:16:37.790 --> 00:16:46.020
some period of time, this is what they found,
this arrow like thing. It's called 'Desulfidorous

00:16:46.020 --> 00:16:56.800
Audaxiator' which is the weirdest microbe
ever found. It is approximately 2.5 miles

00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:02.080
down underground. It has been utterly cut
off from the surface of the Earth for they

00:17:02.080 --> 00:17:07.829
think 10 to 40 million years, meaning that
it has gotten no organic material, nothing

00:17:07.829 --> 00:17:15.409
that had to do with photosynthesis. It lives,
its energy source is the radioactive decay

00:17:15.409 --> 00:17:24.360
of rocks and it, it uses that to break hydrogen
sulfide into elements that it can use to metabolize

00:17:24.360 --> 00:17:31.960
and survive. It reproduces very slowly but
it reproduces. And as far as we can tell at

00:17:31.960 --> 00:17:39.570
this point, it is, it is prevalent through
this, this area of, of South Africa. And the

00:17:39.570 --> 00:17:46.470
implication of it is it's probably prevalent
or something like it is right below us too.

00:17:46.470 --> 00:17:53.220
This is a whole new world that no one really
imagined more than 10 years ago that, that

00:17:53.220 --> 00:17:59.200
the, that the microbial life deep down below
us actually there's probably a greater mass

00:17:59.200 --> 00:18:07.450
of that than there is of life above the surface
of Earth.

00:18:07.450 --> 00:18:11.590
This is just to show you that I indeed went
down there. It was very, very hot. It was,

00:18:11.590 --> 00:18:20.470
the ambient temperature was about 140 degrees.
A hundred and sixty degrees inside the walls

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:28.539
and the, something that I had not fully understood
was that there's a lot, there's a lot of water

00:18:28.539 --> 00:18:32.331
that comes through these through the little
fissures in rocks. And that sometimes there

00:18:32.331 --> 00:18:38.850
are lakes and ponds within the rock and that's
where these microbes can live. And a lot of

00:18:38.850 --> 00:18:47.370
it is just within the fissures of rocks. And,
and again, they, but they, they get the water

00:18:47.370 --> 00:18:51.570
they need to get to do the tests from the
bore holes that are put in there. They get

00:18:51.570 --> 00:18:58.190
it and they bring it back up. The, the aspect
of, of being down there that I found most

00:18:58.190 --> 00:19:06.529
remarkable, it is very stark, very hot, very,
it feels like that if there is any place on

00:19:06.529 --> 00:19:10.750
Earth where you're not going to find something
living, it's here. But as because of what

00:19:10.750 --> 00:19:16.490
I knew, you walk through these miles of caves
or of tunnels and you realize there's life

00:19:16.490 --> 00:19:27.679
everywhere. It's just like this little microscopic
stuff and it's in the rocks. And remember

00:19:27.679 --> 00:19:34.679
my, to get to us, you need microbes so that's
where it all starts. Okay.

00:19:34.679 --> 00:19:40.590
NASA is, the consensus view now and this is
again a, a, quite a new thing within the last

00:19:40.590 --> 00:19:45.070
five or 10 years. The consensus view is that
Mars had a period four billion years or so

00:19:45.070 --> 00:19:51.529
ago where it was quite wet and it was warm.
It had a mag -- some kind of magnetic field

00:19:51.529 --> 00:19:56.320
which helped keep it, keep an atmosphere in
place which allowed for all of this to happen.

00:19:56.320 --> 00:20:01.350
This is obviously a rendering rather than
a reality but we, we know that there are all

00:20:01.350 --> 00:20:10.519
these gullies and deltas and whatever else.
And so there is now this view that Mars was

00:20:10.519 --> 00:20:15.830
a potentially habitable place during that
period. This however was Earth at roughly

00:20:15.830 --> 00:20:22.149
that period. We were getting clobbered by
a large, by a small planet that knocked into

00:20:22.149 --> 00:20:31.529
us, became the moon. It was an extremely uninhabitable
place for probably half a billion years or

00:20:31.529 --> 00:20:41.690
more. Through, through some of this geomicrobiology,
there has been the dates of the early, of

00:20:41.690 --> 00:20:47.590
the detection of the earliest microbial life
goes back to about 3.8 billion years meaning

00:20:47.590 --> 00:20:56.300
that life as far as we can tell began very
quickly. Either that it began very quickly

00:20:56.300 --> 00:21:01.499
between roughly 4 billion and 3.8 billion
years and we have no idea how this happened.

00:21:01.499 --> 00:21:09.700
But either it began very quickly or microbes
can live in very complicated, harsh environments.

00:21:09.700 --> 00:21:17.249
An asteroid hits Mars, kicks up some, some
rocks that have microbes in them. They troll

